75
00:04:36.220 --> 00:04:40.080
It's my pleasure to begin this session and to introduce, first,

76
00:04:40.460 --> 00:04:42.170
some concepts around plasticity.

77
00:04:42.760 --> 00:04:46.210
So in the background here, you see an African michaela zene

78
00:04:46.320 --> 00:04:50.100
butterfly. And why would we start a cancer session with a

79
00:04:50.120 --> 00:04:54.100
butterfly? It's because this particular butterfly undergoes a pretty

80
00:04:54.120 --> 00:04:56.660
dramatic phenotypic plasticity.

81
00:04:57.050 --> 00:05:00.760
And so in response to its environment, whether it's a dry or it's the wet

82
00:05:00.860 --> 00:05:04.360
season, in Africa, it'll actually change its wing

83
00:05:04.480 --> 00:05:07.980
patterns in a fairly dramatic way. This isn't genetically regulated.

84
00:05:08.020 --> 00:05:11.450
It's an epigenomic and transcriptionally regulated

85
00:05:11.480 --> 00:05:15.440
process. And so plasticity, in the case of the butterfly, is really the ability

86
00:05:15.480 --> 00:05:19.469
of the organism to change its phenotype in response to the environment.

87
00:05:19.830 --> 00:05:22.930
And today, we're going to be talking about cellular plasticity in the context of

88
00:05:22.980 --> 00:05:26.930
cancer, where cancer cells can also change their phenotype

89
00:05:27.240 --> 00:05:31.200
non-genetically, and most often in response to the microenvironment.

90
00:05:31.840 --> 00:05:35.650
In cancer, we can assume that plasticity should confer a tremendous

91
00:05:35.720 --> 00:05:39.650
selective advantage, should allow cells to evade the immune system, to spread,

92
00:05:40.200 --> 00:05:43.010
and to evade therapy, and so it's a very important problem in

93
00:05:43.040 --> 00:05:46.716
cancer.So what does plasticity look like, and how do we

94
00:05:46.756 --> 00:05:50.476
understand it? The first is really histologically in a loss of structure

95
00:05:50.496 --> 00:05:54.256
function. It's first seen well over 150 years ago now with the

96
00:05:54.316 --> 00:05:58.156
advent of the first microscopes by Kannheim and Geronte, and then Virchow.

97
00:05:58.596 --> 00:06:00.396
It's really the loss of structure function.

98
00:06:00.476 --> 00:06:03.476
And so this would be the loss of

99
00:06:04.016 --> 00:06:07.376
glands, tape structures, et cetera, and the acquisition of what looks

100
00:06:07.416 --> 00:06:10.956
increasingly like embryonic-like structures within the tissue.

101
00:06:11.676 --> 00:06:15.456
We see this, and we'll see it today with adenosquamous type conversions, as well as

102
00:06:15.466 --> 00:06:19.276
a number of malignancies or transformations during malignancies, such as

103
00:06:19.316 --> 00:06:20.836
neuroendocrine prostate cancer.

104
00:06:21.676 --> 00:06:25.205
Below, I'm showing you a picture of something I'll be talking about,

105
00:06:25.296 --> 00:06:29.236
dedifferentiated endometrial cancer, where you can see in stark contrast

106
00:06:29.276 --> 00:06:33.146
to the fairly well-differentiated areas here, we have

107
00:06:33.216 --> 00:06:36.716
very poorly differentiated areas right next to it.

108
00:06:37.916 --> 00:06:41.696
In addition, there's functional plasticity, which is more of a coordinated program

109
00:06:41.716 --> 00:06:44.316
wherein cells can actually behave like other cell types.

110
00:06:44.836 --> 00:06:48.595
One of my favorite examples of this is from my previous mentor, Mary Hendrix,

111
00:06:48.976 --> 00:06:52.676
in work that was done in 2002. In this particular study, they took

112
00:06:52.716 --> 00:06:56.296
melanoma cells, so very aggressive melanoma cells, labeled them with an

113
00:06:56.376 --> 00:07:00.016
RFP protein, and then injected them into the ischemic limb of a

114
00:07:00.056 --> 00:07:03.936
mouse. And so in an ischemic limb model, there's neovascularization, as you

115
00:07:03.976 --> 00:07:07.926
can see here, with a green dextran and beads that

116
00:07:07.936 --> 00:07:11.216
can move through it. And what is truly remarkable is that the red

117
00:07:11.636 --> 00:07:15.096
melanoma cells were forming chimeric vessels with the endothelial cells.

118
00:07:15.386 --> 00:07:19.226
So these weren't melanoma cells becoming endothelial cells, but rather co-opting

119
00:07:19.256 --> 00:07:23.116
certain features of those cells, in this case, the expression of VE-cadherin.

120
00:07:25.016 --> 00:07:28.916
And finally, we have the movement between cellular states and fates, which is sort

121
00:07:28.956 --> 00:07:31.776
of where we are right now with concepts of lineage plasticity.

122
00:07:32.616 --> 00:07:36.436
This was described many years ago now with EMT and then MET, so

123
00:07:36.476 --> 00:07:40.326
epithelial-mesenchymal transition and then the opposite, where it's thought

124
00:07:40.356 --> 00:07:44.326
that cells can actually acquire mesenchymal phenotypes, spread and metastasize,

125
00:07:44.356 --> 00:07:46.596
and then colonize with epithelial phenotypes.

126
00:07:47.016 --> 00:07:50.376
And as you can see in this cartoon here, overlaid on a Waddington's

127
00:07:50.416 --> 00:07:54.396
epigenetic landscape, it can also be simply heterogeneity

128
00:07:54.456 --> 00:07:57.636
and cells moving through different epigenomic patterns in order to

129
00:07:57.676 --> 00:07:59.396
display plasticity.

130
00:08:00.596 --> 00:08:04.276
And so we do consider and understand plasticity in the context

131
00:08:04.336 --> 00:08:07.776
of epigenetics. So here I'm showing a cartoon of Waddington's

132
00:08:07.816 --> 00:08:10.896
epigenomic landscape that was co-opted by Dr.

133
00:08:10.956 --> 00:08:14.896
Yamanaka several years ago now. And so within this, we have

134
00:08:14.956 --> 00:08:18.036
what would be considered a totipotent cell at the top of the hill.

135
00:08:18.386 --> 00:08:22.036
And during development, in response to developmental cues and microenvironmental

136
00:08:22.136 --> 00:08:26.056
factors, there's cell fate specification until you eventually lead to

137
00:08:26.096 --> 00:08:28.456
the various cell types within the body.

138
00:08:29.416 --> 00:08:33.276
It was considered very difficult to transdifferentiate or move between these

139
00:08:33.336 --> 00:08:37.156
epigenomic states, and even more difficult to move back up the

140
00:08:37.196 --> 00:08:41.096
trajectory. And of course, Dr. Yamanaka showed that this is actually quite easy and

141
00:08:41.136 --> 00:08:43.756
can occur with just three or so factors.

142
00:08:43.776 --> 00:08:46.836
And since then, we've shown that this can occur with cocktails within the

143
00:08:46.876 --> 00:08:50.476
microenvironment. Superimposed upon this, I added my small

144
00:08:50.516 --> 00:08:53.936
addition, which are the lightning bolts, which is a context of cancer wherein we

145
00:08:53.976 --> 00:08:57.905
have mutations. And certain mutations, like the loss of P53, can

146
00:08:57.956 --> 00:09:01.776
actually dramatically increase the ability of cells to reprogram and move

147
00:09:01.836 --> 00:09:05.316
up that hill. There's something about the interplay of genomic

148
00:09:05.356 --> 00:09:09.036
instability and mutations and epigenomic instability that occurs in

149
00:09:09.096 --> 00:09:09.516
cancer.

150
00:09:10.656 --> 00:09:13.376
And so I bring you to our session today. We're going to start with Dr.

151
00:09:13.456 --> 00:09:17.036
Lupien, who's going to be talking to us about this interplay and the

152
00:09:17.076 --> 00:09:20.916
heterogeneity in genomic mutations that can

153
00:09:20.936 --> 00:09:24.716
occur concomitantly with alterations in the epigenome, and how

154
00:09:24.736 --> 00:09:28.636
these work together to enable plasticity as well as

155
00:09:28.856 --> 00:09:30.456
heterogeneity within tumors.

156
00:09:31.356 --> 00:09:34.976
I'll then be talking about dedifferentiated endometrial cancer and trying to get at

157
00:09:34.996 --> 00:09:38.256
some of the mechanistic underpinnings by which cells can go from something that

158
00:09:38.276 --> 00:09:41.936
looks fairly well differentiated into something that looks embryonic-like.

159
00:09:43.016 --> 00:09:46.756
And finally, Hongbin Ji will be talking about his work related to lung

160
00:09:46.816 --> 00:09:50.536
cancer and adenosquamous conversions, and trying to

161
00:09:50.576 --> 00:09:54.386
understand signaling pathways that may mediate this so that we can inhibit this

162
00:09:54.416 --> 00:09:58.185
particular process, and notably looking at how factors in the microenvironment,

163
00:09:58.256 --> 00:10:01.176
such as inflammation, can help to promote these conversions.

164
00:10:02.595 --> 00:10:05.456
And with that, I'll invite Dr. Lupien to the stage.

165
00:10:14.216 --> 00:10:17.996
All right. So, thank you for the organizers, for the chair, for

166
00:10:18.396 --> 00:10:20.176
enabling us to come here and present our work.

167
00:10:20.676 --> 00:10:23.956
So today, I'll be talking about epigenetic heterogeneity or epigenomic

168
00:10:23.976 --> 00:10:27.876
heterogeneity and how it enables tumor evolution, how it

169
00:10:27.956 --> 00:10:30.536
assists in the process of tumor evolution.

170
00:10:30.616 --> 00:10:34.186
And when I use the term epigenetics, epigenomics, I want to be specific about what

171
00:10:34.236 --> 00:10:37.656
I'm talking about. I'm actually specifically talking about the chromatin

172
00:10:37.816 --> 00:10:38.316
itself,

173
00:10:39.256 --> 00:10:42.656
from the policy in the lab or whatever the mindset in the lab, which stands for

174
00:10:43.036 --> 00:10:46.936
that, yes, DNA might hold the words in our genome, but it

175
00:10:46.996 --> 00:10:49.916
is the chromatin that tells the story. Okay, good.

176
00:10:50.596 --> 00:10:52.856
I have no conflict to report for this presentation.

177
00:10:53.356 --> 00:10:56.256
So what do I mean by chromatin so that we're all on the same page?

178
00:10:57.156 --> 00:11:00.596
Going back to Biology 101, chromatin is this

179
00:11:00.636 --> 00:11:04.416
complex of DNA and proteins that actually is found in living

180
00:11:04.476 --> 00:11:08.356
cells, where you have specific proteins known as histones that come in,

181
00:11:08.416 --> 00:11:11.996
form an octamer around which 147 base pairs of

182
00:11:12.036 --> 00:11:15.896
DNA will wrap, and that will define what we call a

183
00:11:15.916 --> 00:11:19.816
nucleosome. And the nucleosome is the basic unit of

184
00:11:19.836 --> 00:11:23.136
the chromatin. There's multiple nucleosomes in cells,

185
00:11:23.196 --> 00:11:26.556
and the spacing between nucleosomes will

186
00:11:26.576 --> 00:11:29.976
define how DNA sequences are actually

187
00:11:30.016 --> 00:11:32.536
interpreted in a given cell as opposed to another.

188
00:11:32.986 --> 00:11:36.976
And so the nucleosomes can be very close to each other, forming a highly compacted

189
00:11:37.056 --> 00:11:40.516
structure, in which case there's not going to be any stretch of DNA

190
00:11:40.796 --> 00:11:44.516
readily available for anything else that could read DNA, such

191
00:11:44.596 --> 00:11:48.476
as DNA-binding proteins, transcription factors, or DNA repair

192
00:11:48.516 --> 00:11:52.256
machinery. But you can also have other areas of your genome where the

193
00:11:52.276 --> 00:11:56.256
nucleosomes are sparse, far away from each other, such that the DNA

194
00:11:56.316 --> 00:12:00.116
in between, the linker DNA, is accessible for

195
00:12:00.216 --> 00:12:03.256
any protein that can read the DNA sequence.

196
00:12:03.286 --> 00:12:06.816
Again, transcription factors, DNA repair machinery, DNA replication

197
00:12:06.896 --> 00:12:10.244
machinery, and so on and so forth.So we're clear on this.

198
00:12:10.304 --> 00:12:13.984
This is where epigenetic lies. It's in this complex of

199
00:12:14.004 --> 00:12:16.864
DNA and histone proteins that make up the chromatin.

200
00:12:17.784 --> 00:12:19.704
And why do we care so much about the chromatin?

201
00:12:19.744 --> 00:12:23.164
Well, there's two specific aspects, and both have to do with the

202
00:12:23.224 --> 00:12:27.144
notion of cell division. When a cell divides, if it wants to

203
00:12:27.184 --> 00:12:30.604
ensure that it maintains its identity, it has to engage in a

204
00:12:30.644 --> 00:12:34.424
replication process that will provide for the daughter cells

205
00:12:34.624 --> 00:12:38.464
equal amount of the critical information that carries the

206
00:12:38.524 --> 00:12:41.324
material, the information that's needed for cell identity.

207
00:12:42.044 --> 00:12:45.624
And while we're all very familiar with the notion of DNA replication,

208
00:12:46.004 --> 00:12:49.664
which happens in vitro in a test tube, what actually happens in the cell

209
00:12:50.204 --> 00:12:53.644
is chromatin replication, such as when the DNA gets

210
00:12:53.684 --> 00:12:57.544
replicated, the histones themselves are also

211
00:12:57.564 --> 00:13:01.504
going to be involved in the process of replication, such that from the

212
00:13:01.584 --> 00:13:05.164
parental DNA, the chromatin, the histones

213
00:13:05.204 --> 00:13:08.844
associated with the parental DNA will split in

214
00:13:08.924 --> 00:13:12.644
half, and half of it will go to the lagging strand, and half of it will go to the

215
00:13:12.704 --> 00:13:16.594
leading strand such that the information present in the parental strand is

216
00:13:16.664 --> 00:13:20.544
still passed down from these histone proteins onto the de

217
00:13:20.604 --> 00:13:24.124
novo synthesized strands. And so this is how a cell

218
00:13:24.164 --> 00:13:27.974
ensures that the material provided for the daughter cells does not only

219
00:13:28.104 --> 00:13:31.964
have a good quality copy of the DNA sequence, but also has a reproducible

220
00:13:32.084 --> 00:13:35.284
copy of the chromatin template from which it came.

221
00:13:36.304 --> 00:13:40.214
The second aspect that's critical about cell division is that when

222
00:13:40.224 --> 00:13:44.204
it's time to divide, there's a Mendelian segregation that happens,

223
00:13:44.244 --> 00:13:48.004
such that you do end up with equal copy of your DNA in the two

224
00:13:48.064 --> 00:13:51.214
daughter cells. This happens with the chromatin as well, right?

225
00:13:51.244 --> 00:13:54.924
Remember this, the chromatin is also segregating in a Mendelian fashion.

226
00:13:54.964 --> 00:13:57.844
And so that's why of all the different molecules that one can study in a cell,

227
00:13:57.884 --> 00:14:01.164
that's why we pay so much attention to the chromatin, because in terms of lineage

228
00:14:01.244 --> 00:14:04.844
fate commitment, if we talk about potency, plasticity, and the likes,

229
00:14:05.584 --> 00:14:09.104
if you want to interfere with cell identity, ultimately you have to be able to

230
00:14:09.124 --> 00:14:12.944
alter the DNA sequence and/or the chromatin state of that

231
00:14:12.984 --> 00:14:16.664
DNA sequence in order to change the identity, the

232
00:14:16.724 --> 00:14:20.564
function of the cells that come out from that replication process.

233
00:14:22.044 --> 00:14:25.684
And so what my lab has been focusing on for a number of years now is

234
00:14:25.864 --> 00:14:29.744
in specifically identifying areas of the genome in cancer

235
00:14:30.304 --> 00:14:34.294
that diverge in chromatin state compared to, let's say, normal tissue,

236
00:14:34.924 --> 00:14:38.424
or when we compare primary to recurrent metastatic tumors.

237
00:14:39.124 --> 00:14:42.064
And so what we do is that we look for what we call chromatin variants.

238
00:14:42.184 --> 00:14:46.024
These areas of the genome that may or may not harbor mutations, but

239
00:14:46.284 --> 00:14:50.164
