00:40:36.428 --> 00:40:40.298
using exome sequencing, but

690
00:40:40.608 --> 00:40:42.748
on a panel of epigenomic marks.

691
00:40:44.168 --> 00:40:47.778
And in doing this, the finding was remarkable that in over

692
00:40:47.848 --> 00:40:51.408
80% of cases, there was a loss of one or up to two

693
00:40:53.208 --> 00:40:56.788
proteins. The first one being SMARCA4, as you can see here, and these are

694
00:40:56.828 --> 00:41:00.008
adjacent regions. And the second one being ARID1B.

695
00:41:00.378 --> 00:41:03.448
And I'll note that in the well-differentiated components of these tumors are

696
00:41:03.508 --> 00:41:06.448
usually ARID1A low. So these would be

697
00:41:06.488 --> 00:41:10.408
ARID1A low, ARID1B deficient

698
00:41:10.468 --> 00:41:14.258
tumors. So why is this important? It turns out that we have

699
00:41:14.328 --> 00:41:18.248
80% of cases that are associated with this, and these hits are

700
00:41:18.268 --> 00:41:22.008
both components of the SWI/SNF chromatin remodeling complex.

701
00:41:22.398 --> 00:41:25.558
And so SMARCA4 is an ATPase within this complex that's

702
00:41:26.148 --> 00:41:28.928
used to generate the energy to help to move nucleosomes.

703
00:41:29.298 --> 00:41:33.108
And ARID1A and ARID1B are mutually exclusive proteins that bind the

704
00:41:33.148 --> 00:41:36.948
DNA. So if you lose both of them, you actually just disrupt the entire complex.

705
00:41:37.508 --> 00:41:41.488
So what we're seeing in the dedifferentiated components of these cancers

706
00:41:41.568 --> 00:41:45.468
is a loss of the SWI/SNF complex. And so we wanted then to

707
00:41:45.508 --> 00:41:48.218
see whether this may be driving dedifferentiation.

708
00:41:48.248 --> 00:41:51.888
So we took cells that would represent the precursor lesion, so they're ARID1A

709
00:41:51.988 --> 00:41:52.268
low,

710
00:41:53.248 --> 00:41:57.188
and did CRISPR genetic manipulations, in order

711
00:41:57.288 --> 00:42:00.772
to genocopy what we were seeing in our patients.Now, the

712
00:42:00.812 --> 00:42:02.352
ARID1A, ARID1B double

713
00:42:03.252 --> 00:42:07.152
loss, we were actually never able to bring cells through the process, but we

714
00:42:07.172 --> 00:42:10.812
were able to do this with SMARCA4 in a couple of cell lines in a couple of ways.

715
00:42:11.492 --> 00:42:15.362
So here we are genocopying what we're seeing in patients, the complete loss of

716
00:42:15.412 --> 00:42:18.352
SMARCA4 with a clonal resolution.

717
00:42:18.822 --> 00:42:22.172
And so we thought, well, if this is the switch, then the loss of SMARCA4

718
00:42:22.312 --> 00:42:25.352
should increase the tumorigenicity of these cells.

719
00:42:25.382 --> 00:42:28.672
And what we saw initially in vitro was really the opposite.

720
00:42:28.742 --> 00:42:32.612
And so you're seeing across the top sphere formation assays, and so this

721
00:42:32.671 --> 00:42:36.172
is just a serial dilution of that. And at the bottom, soft agar

722
00:42:36.252 --> 00:42:38.312
assays, the light gray would be the knockouts.

723
00:42:38.632 --> 00:42:42.572
And it's just clear in all the models, we in fact are seeing an initial

724
00:42:42.592 --> 00:42:45.532
reduction in tumorigenicity and in sphere formation.

725
00:42:46.332 --> 00:42:49.732
And so we went back to the drawing board and thought about plasticity in general.

726
00:42:50.072 --> 00:42:54.012
And so this is another paper that's well over 100 years ago, done

727
00:42:54.092 --> 00:42:56.272
100 years ago by John George Adami.

728
00:42:56.302 --> 00:43:00.292
And Adami was a pathologist that again was looking at tissues, and this

729
00:43:00.302 --> 00:43:03.112
is the paper that he wrote, so making a beautiful observation.

730
00:43:03.452 --> 00:43:07.202
But it's essentially saying that perhaps in cases of plasticity, you don't

731
00:43:07.292 --> 00:43:11.272
have proliferation, and that so as cells are changing or gain the ability to

732
00:43:11.332 --> 00:43:15.252
change and acquire another cell state, they aren't in fact

733
00:43:15.272 --> 00:43:17.902
proliferating. And we know from lineage

734
00:43:19.152 --> 00:43:22.812
plasticity studies, as well as a number of others, that the microenvironment is

735
00:43:22.892 --> 00:43:25.232
also very important. And so we have

736
00:43:26.372 --> 00:43:29.572
Paget, the seed-soil theories, as well as Dr.

737
00:43:29.652 --> 00:43:33.432
Fidler, who has these sort of sequential acquisition of metastases,

738
00:43:33.472 --> 00:43:37.412
particularly in melanoma model, showing that the microenvironment

739
00:43:37.452 --> 00:43:41.072
is very important and can also help to select for different types of phenotypes.

740
00:43:41.482 --> 00:43:45.352
And so we thought that we would take this model and move straight to the mouse.

741
00:43:45.412 --> 00:43:47.352
And so what you're seeing here is what we did.

742
00:43:48.092 --> 00:43:51.862
So we took cancer cells with knockout or wild type SMARCA4, and

743
00:43:51.912 --> 00:43:54.752
then did serial dilutions through the mouse.

744
00:43:54.832 --> 00:43:57.432
So grew a tumor, broke it up, grew another tumor, et cetera.

745
00:43:57.932 --> 00:44:01.752
And what we found in the first passage, so the F0 passage, was the knockouts, very

746
00:44:01.832 --> 00:44:05.132
much like in vitro, had a much lower take rate.

747
00:44:05.392 --> 00:44:07.672
And then when they did grow, they grew slower.

748
00:44:08.292 --> 00:44:11.252
But this was overcome over time till eventually

749
00:44:12.072 --> 00:44:15.552
the knockouts and the wild types had similar growth patterns.

750
00:44:16.872 --> 00:44:20.852
When we remove the cells from that F2 or F3 tumors

751
00:44:20.862 --> 00:44:24.792
and we put them in vivo, you can see that this ability to form tumor spheres

752
00:44:25.092 --> 00:44:28.812
was restored and that in fact the tumor spheres themselves looked quite different.

753
00:44:28.852 --> 00:44:32.752
So we were hopeful that perhaps we had induced this dedifferentiated

754
00:44:32.792 --> 00:44:36.512
phenotype. And indeed, the tumors themselves had characteristics of a

755
00:44:36.532 --> 00:44:40.442
dedifferentiated cancer. And so this is just one example where we're showing that

756
00:44:40.472 --> 00:44:44.292
like the human patients, the tumors

757
00:44:44.332 --> 00:44:47.212
became resistant to chemotherapy, in this case carboplatin.

758
00:44:48.772 --> 00:44:50.592
So what did these cancers look like?

759
00:44:50.672 --> 00:44:54.182
So I'll remind you that when we do our CRISPR workflows, we're actually selecting

760
00:44:54.212 --> 00:44:58.072
for clones. And in cancer biology, we normally don't want to do this, but here for

761
00:44:58.092 --> 00:45:02.052
hypothesis, we actually did. And what we found blew

762
00:45:02.072 --> 00:45:06.032
our minds, which is that these tumors weren't undifferentiated,

763
00:45:06.092 --> 00:45:09.292
which is what we thought, but were rather properly dedifferentiated.

764
00:45:09.692 --> 00:45:12.062
So you can see on the left-hand side are model system.

765
00:45:12.372 --> 00:45:15.432
On the right-hand side are actually tissues from patients.

766
00:45:15.932 --> 00:45:19.562
This would be the well-differentiated and undifferentiated

767
00:45:19.572 --> 00:45:23.472
components of the same patient. And I'll just highlight here we have SMARCA4

768
00:45:23.492 --> 00:45:27.432
knocked out on this side. And you can see by the hatched lines

769
00:45:27.552 --> 00:45:29.842
in H&amp;E they begin to dedifferentiate.

770
00:45:30.312 --> 00:45:34.172
They start to lose markers such as E-cadherin, as well as lineage markers such as

771
00:45:34.232 --> 00:45:37.752
PAX8. But the notable thing was that we saw both well and poorly

772
00:45:37.772 --> 00:45:40.752
differentiated components within the same tumor.

773
00:45:41.782 --> 00:45:44.572
Which caused us to ask how this was actually happening.

774
00:45:44.592 --> 00:45:47.972
So this could have been another stochastic event that would be indicated by a

775
00:45:47.992 --> 00:45:51.792
mutation or perhaps a hierarchical reprogramming that we should be

776
00:45:51.852 --> 00:45:54.332
able to see with epigenomic changes

777
00:45:54.592 --> 00:45:58.392
genome-wide. And so this is just showing that it is

778
00:45:58.892 --> 00:46:01.232
very unlikely to be a genomic alteration.

779
00:46:01.252 --> 00:46:04.172
So here we're looking at pooled tumors, and this is repeated.

780
00:46:04.212 --> 00:46:07.952
We took cells before they go into the animal and then cells at F2 or

781
00:46:08.032 --> 00:46:11.832
F3 and did these comparisons. So on the left-hand side is just a

782
00:46:11.892 --> 00:46:15.792
summary of exome sequencing that was conducted, really with just a focus

783
00:46:15.832 --> 00:46:19.732
on highly mutated genes. I'll note that the background of these cancers is

784
00:46:19.792 --> 00:46:22.692
MSI high, so they have a high mutational burden.

785
00:46:22.852 --> 00:46:26.402
So we would expect some noise and variability.

786
00:46:26.412 --> 00:46:30.392
On the left-hand side are the wild type cells and tumors, and then the right side,

787
00:46:30.592 --> 00:46:34.282
the knockout cells and tumors. And I'll just note that there really isn't

788
00:46:34.352 --> 00:46:38.112
anything popping up at a high frequency in the knockout

789
00:46:38.192 --> 00:46:41.982
tumors. That would suggest to us that this is driving dedifferentiation.

790
00:46:42.412 --> 00:46:46.282
And I will note that at the time that we take these tumors, they are about 50%

791
00:46:46.312 --> 00:46:50.122
undifferentiated. So we have a very low frequency of some mutations and

792
00:46:50.172 --> 00:46:53.432
really nothing that is different from what we're seeing in the wild type.

793
00:46:53.472 --> 00:46:55.912
We think this is actually reflective of the MSI

794
00:46:56.772 --> 00:47:00.292
phenotype. This is DNA methylation array that was also

795
00:47:00.312 --> 00:47:04.172
conducted. And what you're seeing here are cells in vitro before they go into the

796
00:47:04.212 --> 00:47:07.802
tumor. And then wild type on this side, knockout on this

797
00:47:07.832 --> 00:47:11.732
side. In here, we have cells that we've taken out

798
00:47:11.772 --> 00:47:15.372
of the tumor and regrown in vitro, and then cells right from the tumor.

799
00:47:16.072 --> 00:47:19.572
And here we have cells right from the tumor and then grown in vitro.

800
00:47:20.392 --> 00:47:23.592
This is just a principal components analysis because it's just a little easier to

801
00:47:23.672 --> 00:47:27.412
see. What you'll note right away is just moving cells from in vitro

802
00:47:27.532 --> 00:47:30.912
to in vivo causes a marked change in

803
00:47:30.952 --> 00:47:33.972
methylation. So we see a hypomethylation in general.

804
00:47:34.432 --> 00:47:38.091
The next point is that we do get a separation of the knockout and the wild

805
00:47:38.152 --> 00:47:38.472
types,

806
00:47:40.632 --> 00:47:44.292
suggesting that at least DNA methylation is at least playing some role

807
00:47:44.652 --> 00:47:47.052
probably in the dedifferentiation that we're seeing.

808
00:47:48.412 --> 00:47:50.932
So we wanted to know then, how are these cancers evolving?

809
00:47:51.012 --> 00:47:53.592
So it looks to be something that's regulated by the epigenome.

810
00:47:54.212 --> 00:47:56.632
So in order to do this, we went back again to the beginning.

811
00:47:56.692 --> 00:48:00.632
We barcoded the populations in vitro, so these would be naive populations in

812
00:48:00.672 --> 00:48:04.532
vitro, and then took them through the entire course of the serial

813
00:48:04.572 --> 00:48:08.462
passaging again, conducting single cell multi-ome sequencing at

814
00:48:08.492 --> 00:48:12.442
each step.So the first thing that we did was look at the barcode

815
00:48:12.482 --> 00:48:15.841
variations. So this is really confirming our exome sequencing.

816
00:48:16.242 --> 00:48:19.762
So if you were to have a mutation or stochastic event that allowed an

817
00:48:19.782 --> 00:48:23.662
expansion of clones in the knockouts, you would expect to see that

818
00:48:24.102 --> 00:48:27.312
in the barcodes, and we saw really no difference between wild types and

819
00:48:27.342 --> 00:48:30.522
knockouts. And in addition, we did mitochondrial

820
00:48:30.722 --> 00:48:34.162
entropy and confirmed again that there's really no difference between wild types

821
00:48:34.202 --> 00:48:37.922
and knockouts. So we're not selecting a clone during this particular process.

822
00:48:38.962 --> 00:48:42.902
This is a single-cell ATAC sequencing that I'm highlighting here, and

823
00:48:42.912 --> 00:48:46.792
I'll point out a few things. These are the wild types here, and

824
00:48:46.822 --> 00:48:50.742
these are our knockouts. So the chromatin occupancy is different

825
00:48:50.762 --> 00:48:52.302
between wild types and knockouts.

826
00:48:52.842 --> 00:48:56.462
I'll also note that while we go through the passaging, the wild types

827
00:48:56.522 --> 00:49:00.442
remain rather uniform sitting here, whereas the knockouts start to

828
00:49:00.542 --> 00:49:04.452
drift over time. And I'm calling this a drift quite intentionally because I

829
00:49:04.862 --> 00:49:08.702
think it's a rather random drift. I've also overlaid on here what

830
00:49:08.882 --> 00:49:12.082
we'll be looking at in a few seconds, which is the RNA clusters.

831
00:49:12.112 --> 00:49:15.982
And what you can notably see is that those clusters are actually shared between the

832
00:49:16.002 --> 00:49:19.642
knockouts and the wild types, albeit in different frequencies.

833
00:49:19.672 --> 00:49:23.322
So what we're seeing is, yes, a different chromatin state, so different

834
00:49:23.342 --> 00:49:27.282
chromatin occupancy, but in fact the same transcriptional states between

835
00:49:27.322 --> 00:49:28.642
the wild types and the knockouts.

836
00:49:29.982 --> 00:49:33.682
And that can be seen here. So this is just the integrated

837
00:49:33.722 --> 00:49:37.212
multi-ome single-cell sequencing that you can see in the various

838
00:49:37.222 --> 00:49:39.582
clusters, wild types, and knockouts here.

839
00:49:39.902 --> 00:49:43.442
And albeit the ratios are different between the two, we really aren't seeing a

840
00:49:43.602 --> 00:49:45.522
difference in the states that they're existing in.

841
00:49:46.962 --> 00:49:50.942
If you recall, we barcoded everything, so we can look in each tumor over

842
00:49:51.002 --> 00:49:54.582
time at the frequency of the states for each cell.

843
00:49:54.622 --> 00:49:58.562
This is showing that all cells actually have the capacity to exist in all of

844
00:49:58.582 --> 00:50:02.381
the states in any given tumor. So this is truly plasticity within that.

845
00:50:03.102 --> 00:50:06.802
Whereas the wild types remain fairly constant between passage,

846
00:50:06.882 --> 00:50:09.682
suggesting that this is probably in response to location within the

847
00:50:09.722 --> 00:50:13.642
microenvironment. We see that the knockouts are erratic

848
00:50:13.702 --> 00:50:17.282
in terms of the frequency of expression of the various states.

849
00:50:19.242 --> 00:50:22.362
So is there anything stem cell-like or embryonic in these cancers?

850
00:50:22.422 --> 00:50:26.142
The answer is startlingly, and to my chagrin, absolutely

851
00:50:26.222 --> 00:50:30.202
not. So we have no embryonic signature. We have no dedifferentiated signature.

852
00:50:30.532 --> 00:50:34.522
And in fact, the only pathway that came out positively was hypoxia in all

853
00:50:34.562 --> 00:50:38.442
of this. And so we have a difference in some mesenchymal genes and other

854
00:50:38.451 --> 00:50:42.332
types of genes. But in general, there definitely is not a

855
00:50:42.742 --> 00:50:45.422
stem cell or developmental signature that's emerging.

856
00:50:46.702 --> 00:50:50.102
So we didn't quite believe it, and we've used a number of other types of assays to

857
00:50:50.182 --> 00:50:53.562
look at this. So what I'm showing you here is an archetype analysis.

858
00:50:53.622 --> 00:50:57.592
So this is really looking at extremes of phenotype or states that

859
00:50:57.622 --> 00:51:01.382
can exist within a population. Again, showing that,

860
00:51:02.002 --> 00:51:04.671
in this case, we have these four states.

861
00:51:05.282 --> 00:51:08.782
And this is different in that it's also using machine learning to extrapolate which

862
00:51:08.802 --> 00:51:11.282
cells are sitting in a non-committed state.

863
00:51:11.342 --> 00:51:12.942
So it's not clustering out everything.

864
00:51:13.582 --> 00:51:17.482
So what you can see is, again, wild types and knockouts are existing in all of

865
00:51:17.522 --> 00:51:20.902
the states. And the notable difference is that the knockouts exist in an

866
00:51:21.102 --> 00:51:23.962
uncommitted state much more frequently than the wild type.

867
00:51:24.302 --> 00:51:28.182
So they're not in an embryonic state. They're more often in an uncommitted state.

868
00:51:29.022 --> 00:51:32.542
And we've confirmed this with other experiments using, for example,

869
00:51:32.622 --> 00:51:34.402
pseudotime and velocity analysis.

870
00:51:34.762 --> 00:51:37.162
So on the right-hand side, we have wild-type tumors.

871
00:51:37.302 --> 00:51:40.022
On the left, I guess it's the other way when you're looking at it.

872
00:51:40.382 --> 00:51:43.302
On this side, we have the knockout tumors, and you can appreciate with the

873
00:51:43.362 --> 00:51:47.122
lightness of color, then the knockout tumors, while they can hit a final

874
00:51:47.202 --> 00:51:48.502
state, are existing in a far

875
00:51:49.482 --> 00:51:53.002
earlier state. So they're much less committed within these transcriptional states,

876
00:51:53.342 --> 00:51:56.802
in contrast to the wild types, which are existing in rather

877
00:51:57.262 --> 00:51:59.582
static states within the tumor.

878
00:52:02.562 --> 00:52:06.382
So collectively, those results suggest to us that dedifferentiation

879
00:52:06.442 --> 00:52:08.222
isn't actually dedifferentiation.

880
00:52:08.262 --> 00:52:11.662
It's not the acquisition of an embryonic phenotype, but rather the

881
00:52:12.262 --> 00:52:14.562
inability of a cell to sit in a set state.

882
00:52:15.042 --> 00:52:18.302
And so we thought if this was the case, then we should be able to go back to the

883
00:52:18.342 --> 00:52:21.922
human tissue samples, look at them, and be able to find

884
00:52:22.182 --> 00:52:25.822
characteristics of a epithelial cell within those

885
00:52:25.862 --> 00:52:29.082
dedifferentiated areas. And so we used a bank of

886
00:52:29.722 --> 00:52:33.142
tissues that we had and looked to see simply whether these areas had

887
00:52:33.182 --> 00:52:34.702
E-cadherin within them.

888
00:52:35.582 --> 00:52:39.522
And you can see with IHC staining, so in red, that we

889
00:52:39.562 --> 00:52:42.782
did in fact see this. So if you didn't have the staining, it kind of plays a trick

890
00:52:42.842 --> 00:52:45.742
on you. You would assume that these were dedifferentiated regions.

891
00:52:46.022 --> 00:52:49.962
But what we discovered was E-cadherin sort of heterogeneously expressed in these

892
00:52:49.982 --> 00:52:51.402
regions, depending on the patients.

893
00:52:51.432 --> 00:52:54.942
And we have this quantified down here to really highlight the

894
00:52:54.962 --> 00:52:57.202
heterogeneity that is existing.

895
00:52:59.582 --> 00:53:03.162
And so, in summary, we have shown that SMARCA4 loss in

896
00:53:03.202 --> 00:53:06.622
endometrial cancer cells does induce a DDEC

897
00:53:06.682 --> 00:53:07.662
histopathology.

898
00:53:08.582 --> 00:53:11.982
And we're careful about this because we don't think it's inducing

899
00:53:12.102 --> 00:53:15.922
dedifferentiation per se. We think that rather SMARCA4

900
00:53:15.982 --> 00:53:19.802
enables cell state disorder. And this can be exemplified with our human

901
00:53:19.902 --> 00:53:23.162
tissues, showing that E-cadherin staining can occur in even

902
00:53:23.222 --> 00:53:26.602
differentiated regions of SMARCA4-deficient

903
00:53:26.802 --> 00:53:30.122
tumors. And in fact, when we're looking at the expression of markers like this

904
00:53:30.182 --> 00:53:33.562
across the different states, they're not defining the states per se.

905
00:53:34.562 --> 00:53:38.502
All cells, both wild type and SMARCA4, can manifest plasticity

906
00:53:38.512 --> 00:53:42.462
in transcriptional states. However, only the knockout cells exhibit

907
00:53:42.522 --> 00:53:45.582
a random transition between states, and we actually think this may be a

908
00:53:45.602 --> 00:53:49.142
detachment from being instructed by the microenvironment.

909
00:53:49.762 --> 00:53:52.672
And that finally, histological dedifferentiation in the case of

910
00:53:52.702 --> 00:53:56.612
DDDC is likely not always due to the reprogramming

911
00:53:56.642 --> 00:53:58.862
towards a stem cell or more embryonic fate.

912
00:54:00.622 --> 00:54:04.022
And so I'll just end thanking the people that did this work.

913
00:54:04.062 --> 00:54:07.702
I've mentioned Mackenzie and Chenghan Li and Martin Kobel.

914
00:54:08.542 --> 00:54:12.282
We've had a lot of help with the informatics by people such as David Knapp,

915
00:54:13.002 --> 00:54:16.662
and Hannah and Julia have taken on this project to sort of understand how

916
00:54:17.062 --> 00:54:20.772
this is actually occurring.I'll take

917
00:54:20.792 --> 00:54:21.332
questions.

918
00:54:33.232 --> 00:54:37.152
Hi, great talk. I noticed in your cartoon model for

919
00:54:37.232 --> 00:54:39.932
your in vivo models that use NSG mice-

920
00:54:40.512 --> 00:54:40.712
Yeah

921
00:54:40.722 --> 00:54:44.212
... do you expect these same epigenetic changes from the chromatin remodeling

922
00:54:44.452 --> 00:54:46.212
knockouts in any immunocompetent mice?

923
00:54:47.032 --> 00:54:50.942
That's a great question. I think the immunocompetent mice would likely have

924
00:54:50.972 --> 00:54:52.592
a pressure from the immune system.

925
00:54:53.692 --> 00:54:57.582
The components such as HLAs also change in this particular

926
00:54:57.652 --> 00:55:01.412
model, and so we don't have that pressure on there, so we're not seeing the

927
00:55:01.452 --> 00:55:05.292
consequences of that. This is really probably cell intrinsic and due more

928
00:55:05.312 --> 00:55:08.752
to features such as hypoxia and nutrient availability or location within the

929
00:55:08.772 --> 00:55:12.692
tumor. But it's a great question and I think it's also part of the reason

930
00:55:12.732 --> 00:55:16.052
why in patients, over time, the well-differentiated component,

931
00:55:16.972 --> 00:55:20.932
it doesn't exist in the final tumors. It's undifferentiated.

932
00:55:21.032 --> 00:55:22.812
I think a lot of that has to do with the immune system.

933
00:55:23.092 --> 00:55:25.832
So it's a great question, and that interplay is really important.

934
00:55:25.892 --> 00:55:28.812
We are missing out in our models, unfortunately, with that.

935
00:55:28.872 --> 00:55:29.312
Okay, thank you.

936
00:55:31.092 --> 00:55:31.572
Yeah. Yes.

937
00:55:31.652 --> 00:55:35.192
So, really interesting talk. Jeff Wahl from the Salk Institute.

938
00:55:36.932 --> 00:55:38.852
So I have two kind of related questions.

939
00:55:40.032 --> 00:55:42.752
One is how you are looking at

940
00:55:44.452 --> 00:55:48.432
the embryonic state. So are you looking at

941
00:55:48.492 --> 00:55:52.412
transcription factors or genes that are expressed in embryonic

942
00:55:52.452 --> 00:55:56.112
stem cells, or are you looking at transcription

943
00:55:56.232 --> 00:55:59.912
factors that are specific to the early embryonic

944
00:56:00.072 --> 00:56:01.732
stages of this tissue?

945
00:56:02.872 --> 00:56:04.012
We have done both.

946
00:56:04.072 --> 00:56:04.252
Mm-hmm.

947
00:56:05.132 --> 00:56:07.812
And neither are popping up in particular.

948
00:56:08.492 --> 00:56:12.262
So my first inclination was that we would-- I have a background looking at

